This is a list of '''important publications''' in [[cryptography]], organized by field.
Some reasons why a particular publication might be regarded as important: *'''Topic creator''' &ndash; A publication that created a new topic *'''Breakthrough''' &ndash; A publication that changed scientific knowledge significantly *'''Influence''' &ndash; A publication which has significantly influenced the world or has had a massive impact on the teaching of cryptography.<!-- The text of this lead section was substituted into this page from [[Template:List of publications intro]]. --><!--An entry in this list should include citations for statements about the importance of the publication. Otherwise it may be challenged and removed.-->
==[[Cryptanalysis]]==
===''The index of coincidence and its applications in cryptology''=== *{{cite journal|last=Friedman|first=William F.|year=1922|title=The index of coincidence and its applications in cryptology|journal=Department of Ciphers. Publ 22.|publisher=Riverbank Laboratories|location=Geneva, Illinois, USA|authorlink=William F. Friedman}}
Description: Presented the [[index of coincidence]] method for [[codebreaking]].
===''Treatise on the Enigma''=== *{{cite book|last=Turing|first=Alan|authorlink=Alan Turing|title=Treatise on the Enigma|url=http://www.turingarchive.org/browse.php/C/30|date= 1939-1942}}
Description: The breaking of the [[Enigma machine|Enigma]].
===''The Codebreakers: The Story of Secret Writing''=== *{{cite book|last=Kahn|first=David|authorlink=David Kahn (writer)|title=[[The Codebreakers]]: The Story of Secret Writing|year=1967|publisher=The Macmillan Company|location=New York|isbn=0-684-83130-9}}
Description: Almost nothing had been published in cryptography in several decades and very few non-government researchers were thinking about it. ''The Codebreakers'', a popular and non academic book, made many more people aware and contains a lot of technical information, although it requires careful reading to extract it. Its 1967 appearance was followed by the appearance of many papers over the next few years.
===Differential Cryptanalysis of DES-like Cryptosystems=== *{{cite journal|authorlink1=Eli Biham |first1=Eli |last1=Biham |authorlink2=Adi Shamir |first2=Adi |last2=Shamir|year=1991|journal=[[Journal of Cryptology]]|volume=4|issue=1|url=http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/biham91differential.html |title=Differential Cryptanalysis of DES-like Cryptosystems |doi=10.1007/bf00630563 |pages=3–72}}
Description: The method of [[differential cryptanalysis]].
===A new method for known plaintext attack of FEAL cipher=== *{{cite book|last1=Matsui|first1=Mitsuru|authorlink1=|first2=Atsuhiro |last2=Yamagishi|year=1993|chapter=A New Method for Known Plaintext Attack of FEAL Cipher|volume=658|pages=81–91|doi=10.1007/3-540-47555-9_7 |series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science|title=Advances in Cryptology — [[EUROCRYPT]] '92}}
Description: The method of [[linear cryptanalysis]].
==Theory==
===Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems=== *{{cite journal|last=Shannon|first=C.E.|authorlink=Claude E. Shannon|year=1949|title=Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems|journal=[[Bell System Technical Journal]]|issue=28-4|pages=656&ndash;715|url=http://netlab.cs.ucla.edu/wiki/files/shannon1949.pdf|doi=10.1002/j.1538-7305.1949.tb00928.x|volume=28}}
Description: [[Information theory]] based analysis of cryptography. The original form of this paper was a confidential Bell Labs report from 1945, not the one published.
===[[Probabilistic Encryption]]=== *{{cite journal|date=April 1984|journal=Journal of Computer and System Sciences|volume=28|issue=2|pages=270–299|url=http://theory.lcs.mit.edu/~cis/pubs/shafi/1984-jcss.pdf|authorlink1=Shafi Goldwasser|first1=Shafi|last1=Goldwasser|authorlink2=Silvio Micali|first2=Silvio |last2=Micali |title=Probabilistic Encryption|doi=10.1016/0022-0000(84)90070-9}}
Description: The paper provides a rigorous basis to encryption (e.g., [[partial information]]) and shows that it possible to equate the slightest cryptanalysis to solve a pure math problem. Second, it introduces the notion of [[computational indistinguishability]].
===Proofs that Yield Nothing But their Validity or All Languages in NP have Zero-Knowledge Proofs=== *{{Cite journal | last1 = Goldreich | first1 = O. |authorlink1=Oded Goldreich| last2 = Micali | first2 = S. |authorlink2=Silvio Micali| last3 = Wigderson | first3 = A. |authorlink3=Avi Wigderson| doi = 10.1145/116825.116852 | title = Proofs that yield nothing but their validity or all languages in NP have zero-knowledge proof systems | journal = Journal of the ACM | volume = 38 | issue = 3 | pages = 690–728 | date=July 1991 | url = http://www.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il/~oded/X/gmw1j.pdf}}
Description: This paper explains how to construct a [[zero-knowledge proof]] system for any language in [[NP (complexity)|NP]].
==[[Private key cryptography]]==
===Cryptographic Coding for Data-Bank Privacy=== * {{cite journal|last=Feistel|first=Horst|authorlink=Horst Feistel|date=18 March 1970|title=Cryptographic Coding for Data-Bank Privacy|journal=[[IBM]] Research Report 2827}}
Description: [[Feistel cipher]]s are a form of cipher of which [[Data Encryption Standard|DES]] is the most important. It would be hard to overestimate the importance of either Feistel or DES. Feistel pushed a transition from stream ciphers to block ciphers. Although most ciphers operate on streams, most of the important ciphers today are block ciphers at their core.
===''[[Data Encryption Standard]]''=== * NBS Federal Standard FIPS PUB 46, 15 Jan 1977.
Description: [[Data Encryption Standard|DES]] is not only one of the most widely deployed ciphers in the world but has had a profound impact on the development of cryptography. Roughly a generation of cryptographers devoted much of their time to attacking and improving DES.
==[[Public Key Cryptography]]==
===New directions in cryptography=== * {{Cite journal | last1 = Diffie | first1 = W. |authorlink1=Whitfield Diffie| last2 = Hellman | first2 = M. |authorlink2=Martin Hellman| doi = 10.1109/TIT.1976.1055638 | title = New directions in cryptography | journal = [[IEEE Transactions on Information Theory]]| volume = 22 | issue = 6 | pages = 644&ndash;654 | year = 1976 | url = //ee.stanford.edu/%7Ehellman/publications/24.pdf}}
Description: This paper suggested [[public key cryptography]] and presented [[Diffie–Hellman key exchange]]. For more information about this work see: [[Whitfield Diffie|W.Diffie]], [[Martin Hellman|M.E.Hellman]], [http://www-ee.stanford.edu/~hellman/publications/32.pdf "Privacy and Authentication: An Introduction to Cryptography"], in [[Proc. IEEE]], Vol 67(3) Mar 1979, pp 397–427.
===On the Signature Reblocking Problem in Public Key Cryptography=== *{{cite journal|last=Kohnfelder|first=Loren M.|year=1978|title=On the Signature Reblocking Problem in Public Key Cryptography|journal=[[Communications of the ACM]]|volume=21|issue=2|page=179|authorlink=Loren Kohnfelder}}
Description: In this paper (along with [[Loren Kohnfelder|Loren M. Kohnfelder]],"Using Certificates for Key Distribution in a Public-Key Cryptosystem", [[MIT]] Technical report 19 May 1978), Kohnfelder introduced [[Academic certificate|certificate]]s (signed messages containing public keys) which are the heart of all modern [[key management system]]s.
===Secure Communications Over Insecure Channels=== * {{Cite journal | last1 = Merkle | first1 = R. C. |authorlink1=Ralph Merkle| title = Secure Communications Over Insecure Channels | doi = 10.1145/359460.359473 | journal = [[Communications of the ACM]]| volume = 21 | issue = 4 | pages = 294–299 | date=April 1978 | pmid = | pmc = }}
Description: This paper introduced a branch of public key [[cryptography]], known as public key distribution systems. Merkle's work predated "New directions in cryptography" though it was published after it. The Diffie–Hellman key exchange is an implementation of such a Merkle system. Hellman himself has argued<ref>http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/qna/0,289202,sid14_gci1077600,00.html</ref> that a more correct name would be Diffie–Hellman–Merkle key exchange.
===A Method for Obtaining Digital Signatures and Public Key Cryptosystems=== * {{Cite journal | last1 = Rivest | first1 = R. L. | authorlink1 = Ron Rivest | last2 = Shamir | first2 = A. | authorlink2 = Adi Shamir | last3 = Adleman | first3 = L. | authorlink3 = Len Adleman | doi = 10.1145/359340.359342 | title = A method for obtaining digital signatures and public-key cryptosystems | journal = [[Communications of the ACM]] | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 120&ndash;126 | year = 1978 | url = http://citeseer.nj.nec.com/rivest78method.html | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20031204194711/http://citeseer.nj.nec.com/rivest78method.html | archivedate = 2003-12-04 | df = }}
Description: The [[RSA (algorithm)|RSA]] encryption method. The first [[public-key]] encryption method.
===How to Share a Secret=== * {{Cite journal | last1 = Shamir | first1 = A. | authorlink1 = Adi Shamir | title = How to share a secret | doi = 10.1145/359168.359176 | journal = [[Communications of the ACM]] | volume = 22 | issue = 11 | pages = 612&ndash;613 | date = November 1979 | url = http://szabo.best.vwh.net/secret.html | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150504091740/http://szabo.best.vwh.net/secret.html | archivedate = 2015-05-04 | df = }}
Description: A safe method for sharing a secret.
===On the security of public key protocols=== *{{cite journal|last1=Dolev|first1=D.|first2=A. |last2=Yao|year=1983|title=On the security of public key protocols|journal=IEEE Transactions on Information Theory|volume=29|issue=2|pages=198–208|issn=0018-9448|doi=10.1109/TIT.1983.1056650}} Description: Introduced the [[Dolev-Yao model|adversarial model]] against which almost all cryptographic protocols are judged.
==[[Cryptographic protocol|Protocol]]s==
===Using encryption for authentication in large networks of computers=== * {{Cite journal | last1 = Needham | first1 = R. M. |authorlink1=Roger Needham| last2 = Schroeder | first2 = M. D. |authorlink2=Michael Schroeder| doi = 10.1145/359657.359659 | title = Using encryption for authentication in large networks of computers | journal = [[Communications of the ACM]]| volume = 21 | issue = 12 | pages = 993–999 | year = 1978 | url = http://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs268/sp02/cached_papers/needham.pdf}}
Description: This paper introduced the basic ideas of cryptographic protocols and showed how both [[secret-key]] and [[public-key]] encryption could be used to achieve authentication.
===Kerberos=== *{{cite journal|last1=Neuman|first1=B.C.|first2=T. |last2=Ts'o|authorlink2=Theodore Ts'o|year=1994|title=Kerberos: an authentication service for computer networks|journal=IEEE Communications Magazine|volume=32|issue=9|pages=33–38|issn=0163-6804|doi=10.1109/35.312841|url=http://gost.isi.edu/publications/kerberos-neuman-tso.html}} *{{cite journal|first1=J. G.|last1=Steiner|first2=B. C.|last2=Neuman|first3=J. I.|last3=Schiller|date=February 1988|title=Kerberos: an authentication service for open network systems|journal=Usenix Conference Proceedings|location=Dallas, Texas|url=ftp://athena-dist.mit.edu/pub/kerberos/doc/usenix.PS}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}
Description: The [[Kerberos (protocol)|Kerberos]] [[authentication]] [[cryptographic protocol|protocol]], which allows individuals communicating over an insecure network to prove their identity to one another in a secure and practical manner.
===A Protocol for Packet Network Interconnection=== *{{cite journal|authorlink1=Vint Cerf |first1=Vint |last1=Cerf |authorlink2=Bob Kahn |first2=Bob |last2=Kahn|year=1974|title=A Protocol for Packet Network Interconnection|journal=IEEE Transactions on Communication Technology|url=http://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/fall06/cos561/papers/cerf74.pdf |doi=10.1109/tcom.1974.1092259 |volume=22 |pages=637–648}}
===A Dynamic Network Architecture=== *{{cite journal|date=May 1992|title=A Dynamic Network Architecture|journal=ACM Transactions on Computer Systems|volume=10|issue=2|url=http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/malley92dynamic.html|first1=Sean W. |last1=O'Malley |authorlink2=Larry L. Peterson |first2=Larry L. |last2=Peterson |doi=10.1145/128899.128901 |pages=110–143}}
Description: Network software in distributed systems.
