[[File:Caporaso lucia.jpg|thumb|Lucia Caporaso in Oberwolfach, 2006]] '''Lucia Caporaso''' is an Italian mathematician, holding a professorship in mathematics at [[Roma Tre University]]. Her research includes work in [[algebraic geometry]], [[arithmetic geometry]], [[tropical geometry]] and [[enumerative geometry]].
==Education and career== Caporaso earned a [[laurea]] from [[Sapienza University of Rome]] in 1989.{{r|cv}} She completed her Ph.D. at [[Harvard University]] in 1993. Her dissertation, ''On a Compactification of the Universal Picard Variety over the Moduli Space of Stable Curves'', was supervised by [[Joe Harris (mathematician)|Joe Harris]].{{r|cv|mgp}}
She became a Benjamin Pierce Assistant Professor of Mathematics at Harvard, a researcher at the [[University of Rome Tor Vergata]], an assistant professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], and an associate professor at the [[University of Sannio]], before moving to Roma Tre as a professor in 2001. Since 2013, she has headed the Department of Mathematics and Physics at Roma Tre.{{r|cv}}
==Recognition== Caporaso was the 1997 winner of the [[Bartolozzi Prize]].{{r|bart}}
She is an invited speaker at the 2018 [[International Congress of Mathematicians]], speaking in the section on algebraic and complex geometry.{{r|icm}}
