{{Infobox person | name = Mike Byster | image = Mike Byster TEDx.png | alt = Mike Byster standing in front of a whiteboard during a TEDx presentation in Naperville, IL. | caption = Mike presenting during a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx]] conference | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|3|5}} | birth_place = [[Skokie, Illinois]] | known_for = Mental math abilities | occupation = | website = [http://www.mikebyster.com/ www.mikebyster.com] }}
'''Michael Byster''' (born March 5, 1959) is an American mathematician, [[mental calculator]], and math educator. He worked as a [[commodities market|commodity trader]] until he quit his job to devote himself to teaching children his methods. He has spoken at over 10,000 schools for free and continues to mentor kids. Mike is able to do many arithmetic problems in his head at very fast speeds.<ref name="Mikes Math" /> During a study done years ago, Byster was claimed to have one of the fastest mathematical minds in the world.<ref name="Mikes Math" /><ref name="WGN Interview"> {{Cite web |url=http://wgntv.com/2017/08/30/one-of-the-fastest-brains-in-the-world-mike-byster-blows-anchors-away-with-brainetics/ |title=One of the Fastest Brains in the World, Mike Byster Blows Anchors Away with Brainetics! |date=2017-08-30 |publisher=WGN-TV |access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref>
==Biography==
===Early life=== Byster was raised along with his older sister in the [[Chicago]] suburb of [[Skokie, Illinois]]. His parents Gloria and Dave encouraged his math shortcuts at a young age.<ref name="Mikes Math">{{cite web | url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=2690724&page=1 | title=Mikes Math | publisher=ABC News | date=September 7, 2007 | accessdate=March 27, 2007 | author=Pisarcik, Kristin}}</ref> He went to [[Niles North High School]] and then attended [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]], graduating with a bachelor's degree in [[finance]] in 1981.
===Career=== Byster used to work at the [[Chicago Mercantile Exchange|mercantile]] exchange, but after his cousin, a math teacher in a Chicago area high school, invited him to show the class his shortcuts for doing [[Numeral system|base 10]] arithmetic, Byster quit his job to devote himself to teaching children his methods.<ref name="Who is Mike Byster">{{cite web | url=http://ledlightsdesign.info/articles/who-is-mike-byster-the-brainetics-279.htm | title=Who Is Mike Byster, The Brainetics Pioneer | accessdate=March 29, 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130218025853/http://ledlightsdesign.info/articles/who-is-mike-byster-the-brainetics-279.htm | archivedate=February 18, 2013 | df= }}</ref> After that, he continued to do shows for free to schools across the United States. In December 2003, he released the website Mike's Math, but this was discontinued in 2007.<ref name="Mikes Math Wayback Archive">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401000000*/http://mikesmath.com | title=Wayback Machine | publisher=Internet Archive | accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> In 2008, Byster produced the Brainetics math and memory system. Byster claims that Brainetics uses both sides of the [[brain]] to process and store information, allowing anyone to recall the information at a fast pace.
===Media appearances=== Mike appeared on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s 20/20 in 2007. From 2007 to 2010, he appeared on television shows multiple times. On January 21, 2010, Mike appeared on Oprah Radio's ''Gayle King'' show.<ref name="Gayle King Show Audio">{{cite video | url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahradio/Math-Whiz-Mike-Byster-Audio | title=Math Whiz Mike Byster | publisher=Harpo, Inc. | date=January 21, 2010 | people=[[Gayle King]], Mike Byster}}</ref> Mike has appeared on [[The Shopping Channel]] in [[Canada]] and [[QVC]] in the United States multiple times. He appeared on [[Fox News]] June 8, 2011. He has also appeared on [[WGN-TV|WGN]] in July 2011, [[Good Day New York]] in August 2011<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/17401456/brainetics | title=Brainetics - New York News | publisher=Fox Television Stations, Inc. | date=2011-08-23 | accessdate=2013-06-21 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202111/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/17401456/brainetics | archivedate=2013-10-29 | df= }}</ref> and then [[Fox News|Fox News Boston]] on October 27, 2011. He was on WBEZ's Afternoon Shift on September 27, 2013.<ref name="NPR Interview with Mike Byster">{{cite interview | title=Teaching math by WBEZ's Afternoon Shift | date=27 September 2013 | accessdate=27 October 2013 | last=Byster | first=Mike | interviewer=Niala Boodhoo | work=WBEZ 91.5 | location=Chicago}}</ref> In November 2016 Mike gave a TEDx talk entitled 'How to Think Like a Genius'.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tg4EadS1zSs Byster, Mike, How to Think Like a Genius, TEDx, November 2016]</ref> On June 26, 2017, Mike competed on the Fox TV competition series Superhuman. Byster won that week's competition and with that received $50,000 and the title of Superhuman.<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chicagoinc/ct-superhuman-mike-byster-20170609-story.html</ref><ref>http://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/local-brainiac-mike-byster-competes-on-superhuman/</ref><ref>https://hiddenremote.com/2017/06/27/superhuman-predictable-spoils-ending-episode/</ref> He is a monthly guest on Maryland radio talk show [[The Rude Awakening Show]].
===Personal life=== Byster got married in the early 1990s and has a son, Josh, to whom he has taught his methods. He currently resides in the northern suburbs of Chicago.<ref name="Mikes Math" /> Byster is Jewish.<ref>https://www.c-j-c.org/news/obit.aspx?id=72674</ref><ref>https://www.jrc-evanston.org/sites/default/files/uploaded_documents/jrc-spring-2011.pdf</ref>
